# Security Standards

Never expose secrets, credentials, or tokens in code, logs, or error responses.
Never hardcode credentials — always use environment variables.
All env vars must be in .env.example with descriptions.

Input handling:
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs
- Parameterized queries only — never string-concatenated SQL
- Validate file upload mime types server-side — never trust file extension alone

Authorization:
- Enforce authorization checks at the service layer, not only the router
- Every endpoint must have explicit auth/permission check defined

Passwords and tokens:
- Passwords hashed with bcrypt, minimum 12 rounds
- Access tokens: 15 minute expiry
- Refresh tokens: rotation on every use
- JWTs must never contain sensitive data in the payload

CORS:
- Explicit allowlist only in all environments
- Never use wildcard (*) in production

Dependencies:
- npm audit run in CI — fail on high or critical severity
- pip audit run in CI — fail on high or critical severity
